# Primary outcomes

Reduction of productivity or inefficiency at work, school, home, or in daily routine was evaluated as a continuous variable with values ranging from 1 (not at all) to 6 (severe). Avoidance of or less participation in hobbies or social activities and interference with relationships with others could not be evaluated due to infrequent self-reported impairment of any severity.

## Secondary outcomes

Symptom severity was compared between menstrual cycle weeks using Kruskal-Wallis rank sum tests.

## Exposures

Exposures included continuous variables with score of 1 (not at all) to 6 (severe) for:

1.  Feeling depressed, sad, "down", "blue" or hopeless, worthless, or guilty

2.  Feeling anxious, tense, "keyed up" or "on edge"

3.  Presence of mood swings (ie, suddenly feeling sad or tearful) or sensitivitivy to rejection/feelings easily hurt

4.  Anger or irritability

5.  Reduced interest in usual activities (work, school, friends, hobbies)

6.  Difficulty concentrating

7.  Feeling lethargic, tired, fatigued, lack of energy

8.  Increased or decreased appetite, overeating, or cravings for specific foods

9.  Increased sleep, napping, difficulty get up when intended, or difficulty getting to sleep or staying asleep the night prior

10. Feeling overwhelmed or unable to cope, out of control

11. Breast tenderness, breast swelling, bloating, weight gain,

12. Headache

13. Joint or muscle pain

Self-reported infection was evaluated as a binary indicator variable. Cycle week was modeled as a nominal factor variable.

# Statistical Analysis

Risk factor analysis was conducted using a linear regression model. Forward stepwise regression was used to determine variable inclusion, given the small sample size, lack of heterogeneity among certain risk factors, and multicollinearity of risk factors. Cycle week was included a priori. Additional variable inclusion was based on model fit using the AIC. Analysis was conducted in R version 4.5.1.

